          <h2>Introduction: The Art of Planetary Observing</h2>
          <p>Planetary observing represents one of amateur astronomy's most rewarding pursuits, revealing dynamic atmospheric features, surface markings, and orbital mechanics invisible to naked eyes. Unlike distant galaxies appearing as static smudges, planets display constant change: Jupiter's cloud bands shift and swirl over hours, Saturn's rings cast moving shadows across the globe, Mars' polar caps grow and shrink seasonally, and Venus displays phases like a miniature Moon. These worlds become real through telescopes—not just points of light, but actual spheres with weather systems, geological features, and observable physics.</p>

          <p>Successful planetary observing demands different skills than deep sky work. Where deep sky observing prioritizes dark skies and large aperture, planetary work emphasizes atmospheric stability, optical quality, and high magnifications. A 4-inch refractor under steady skies outperforms a 10-inch reflector under turbulent air for planets. Mastering planetary observation requires understanding seeing conditions, selecting optimal magnifications, timing observations for oppositions, and using filters effectively to enhance contrast.</p>

          <p>This guide covers comprehensive planetary observing techniques for all major planets visible through backyard telescopes: Jupiter (the king with its Great Red Spot and four Galilean moons), Saturn (the jewel with its magnificent ring system), Mars (the red planet revealing polar caps and dark surface markings), Venus and Mercury (challenging inner planets showing phases), and even distant Uranus and Neptune (faint disks requiring careful technique). We'll explore when to observe each planet, what magnifications to use, which filters enhance features, and how to recognize atmospheric conditions that make or break planetary sessions.</p>
