          <h2>Observing Jupiter: The Gas Giant King</h2>
          <p>Jupiter dominates planetary observing with its large apparent size (40-50 arcseconds diameter), bright magnitude (-2.5 at opposition), and dynamic atmospheric features visible even in small telescopes. Jupiter's rapid 10-hour rotation means cloud features cross the visible disk within hours, creating constantly changing views that reward extended observation sessions.</p>

          <h3>What to Look For</h3>
          <p><strong>Cloud Bands and Zones:</strong> Jupiter's atmosphere organizes into alternating dark belts and bright zones parallel to the equator. Even small telescopes (3-4 inches at 80x) show the two prominent equatorial belts (North and South Equatorial Belts) flanking the bright Equatorial Zone. Larger apertures (6+ inches at 150x+) resolve multiple additional belts in northern and southern hemispheres: North and South Temperate Belts, North and South Tropical Zones, and subtle high-latitude bands. The belts represent descending air and lower-altitude clouds, while zones are rising air and high-altitude clouds—creating counter-rotating wind systems with speeds reaching 640 km/h.</p>

          <p><strong>The Great Red Spot (GRS):</strong> Jupiter's iconic storm, a high-pressure anticyclone larger than Earth, appears as an elongated oval in the South Equatorial Belt region. Currently spanning approximately 16,000 km (down from 40,000+ km in the 1800s), the GRS displays salmon-orange to tan coloration depending on year and atmospheric chemistry. Visible in 4-inch telescopes at 120x+ as a subtle oval brightening, 6+ inch telescopes at 150x+ show it clearly with distinct color and structure. The GRS rotates into view approximately every 10 hours—consult GRS transit predictions to time observations. Look for dark "hooks" at leading and trailing edges where the spot's circulation interacts with surrounding jet streams.</p>

          <p><strong>Festoons and Projections:</strong> Dark festoons—thread-like projections from belts into zones—become visible in 6+ inch telescopes during good seeing at 180x+. These features represent vortices and atmospheric disturbances. The Equatorial Zone sometimes displays dark festoons extending from the South Equatorial Belt northward. Northern belts occasionally show similar features. Festoons change within hours, making them fascinating targets for systematic observation.</p>

          <p><strong>White Ovals:</strong> Small white storms appear occasionally as bright ovals in various belts and zones. These anticyclonic storms rival small terrestrial hurricanes in size. Several prominent white ovals orbit at similar latitudes to the GRS, sometimes interacting with it. They're visible in 6+ inch telescopes at 150x+ during good seeing.</p>

          <p><strong>Galilean Moons:</strong> Jupiter's four largest moons (Io, Europa, Ganymede, Callisto) appear as bright points flanking the planet, visible in any telescope and even binoculars. Their configurations change nightly as they orbit Jupiter. At high magnifications, you can observe moon transits (moons crossing Jupiter's disk) appearing as small dark dots, moon shadows cast on Jupiter's cloud tops, and moon eclipses (moons disappearing into Jupiter's shadow). Moon transit events add drama to Jupiter observing sessions.</p>

          <h3>Optimal Jupiter Observing</h3>
          <p><strong>Magnification:</strong> Use 100x-150x for general viewing showing full disk with major belts, zones, and GRS. Push to 180x-250x during excellent seeing to resolve festoons, white ovals, and fine cloud structure. Maximum useful magnification on stable nights can reach 300x+ in 8+ inch telescopes, revealing incredible atmospheric detail.</p>

          <p><strong>Filters:</strong> Light blue (#80A or #82A) enhances belt contrast, making dark belts appear darker and bright zones brighter. Orange (#21) or light red (#23A or #25) improves GRS contrast and visibility of festoons. Yellow-green (#11) provides balanced enhancement of multiple features. Many observers keep several filters accessible, comparing views to determine which shows target features best on a given night.</p>

          <p><strong>Timing:</strong> Observe Jupiter at opposition for maximum size and brightness. Jupiter oppositions occur annually, advancing by about one month each year (due to Earth's faster orbit). In 2026, Jupiter reaches opposition in late October. The planet remains well-placed for several months surrounding opposition. Check GRS transit predictions if specifically targeting the spot—it's visible for about 50 minutes before and after central meridian crossing.</p>

          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Start at low magnification (80x) to center Jupiter and check seeing quality. Increase to 120-150x for general observation. During moments of good seeing, push to 200x+ to capture fine details. Sketch what you see, noting time, magnification, filters, and seeing quality. Observe for extended sessions (60+ minutes) to watch features rotate across the disk—Jupiter's 10-hour rotation means visible motion occurs within an hour.</p>
