        <section id="outer-planets" class="content-section">
          <h2>The Outer Planets: Uranus and Neptune</h2>
          <p>Uranus and Neptune challenge observers with their extreme distance, small apparent size, and faint magnitudes. While both are technically visible to naked eyes under perfect conditions (Uranus at magnitude 5.7, Neptune at 7.8), seeing them as actual disks rather than star-like points requires telescopes and technique.</p>

          <h3>Uranus</h3>
          <p>Uranus orbits at 19 AU (astronomical units) from the Sun, requiring 84 years to complete one orbit. It appears as a tiny 3.7 arcsecond greenish-blue disk at opposition. The planet's peculiar characteristic—an axial tilt of 98 degrees meaning it rotates on its side—creates unusual seasonal patterns.</p>

          <p><strong>Observing Uranus:</strong> Locate Uranus using planetarium software—it appears star-like to naked eyes. Through telescopes at 100x-150x, Uranus reveals its disk as a small, fuzzy greenish dot distinctly non-stellar. The color (from methane absorption) is apparent even in small telescopes. At 200x+ in 8+ inch telescopes under excellent seeing, Uranus grows to a small but definite disk. Seeing atmospheric bands or surface detail requires professional-class equipment and ideal conditions—amateur observations focus on simply resolving the disk and detecting color.</p>

          <p>Uranus' five major moons (Miranda, Ariel, Umbriel, Titania, Oberon) orbit in the planet's equatorial plane. The moons appear as faint points (magnitude 13-14) requiring 8+ inch telescopes and dark skies to detect. Planetary photography reveals them more easily than visual observation. Charting moon positions over nights demonstrates orbital motion—a satisfying exercise showing these worlds' reality despite tiny appearance.</p>

          <h3>Neptune</h3>
          <p>Neptune orbits at 30 AU, requiring 165 years per orbit—it completed its first full orbit since discovery in 2011. At magnitude 7.8 and just 2.3 arcseconds diameter, Neptune pushes visual telescope limits.</p>

          <p><strong>Observing Neptune:</strong> Finding Neptune requires accurate charts—at 8th magnitude, it's invisible to naked eyes and blends with background stars. Once located, Neptune appears at 100x as a tiny blue-gray dot barely distinguishable from a star. At 200x+ in 8+ inch telescopes, it resolves as a small but definite disk with rich blue color (again from methane). No amateur telescope shows surface detail—Neptune's remote location and small size defeat backyard optics. The observation's satisfaction comes from the contemplation: you're seeing reflected sunlight from a world 4.5 billion kilometers away, requiring 4 hours for light to travel from Neptune to your eye.</p>

          <p>Neptune's largest moon, Triton (magnitude 13.5), orbits in a retrograde direction suggesting capture origin. Triton is detectable in 8+ inch telescopes as a faint point near Neptune—challenging but achievable from dark sites. Distinguishing Triton from background stars requires multiple night observations to confirm orbital motion.</p>

