          <h2>Planetary Filters Guide</h2>
          <p>Color filters enhance planetary observations by selectively blocking certain wavelengths while transmitting others, increasing contrast between features that naturally differ in color. Planetary atmospheric components and surface materials reflect and absorb different wavelengths—filters exploit these differences to make features more apparent.</p>

          <h3>How Planetary Filters Work</h3>
          <p>Planets shine by reflected sunlight containing all visible wavelengths. Different atmospheric chemicals and surface materials reflect specific wavelengths more strongly: Jupiter's reddish-brown belts reflect longer wavelengths (red, orange), while bright zones reflect all wavelengths more uniformly. Using an orange or red filter blocks blue and green wavelengths (which both belts and zones reflect) while passing red-orange wavelengths (which belts reflect strongly, zones reflect weakly)—creating enhanced contrast that makes belts appear darker and zones brighter.</p>

          <p>This principle extends across planets: Mars' ferric oxide deserts reflect red strongly (hence Mars' red appearance), while basaltic plains reflect red weakly—red filters increase this contrast. Venus' UV-absorbing atmospheric components create patterns invisible in visible light but apparent through violet filters. Understanding what you're trying to see guides filter selection.</p>

          <h3>Essential Planetary Filters</h3>
          <p><strong>Light Red #23A or #25 (Red filters):</strong> The most versatile planetary filters, working well on Jupiter, Mars, and Saturn. On Jupiter, red filters enhance belt/zone contrast, improve Great Red Spot visibility, and make festoons more apparent. On Mars, they dramatically increase surface feature contrast, making dark albedo markings like Syrtis Major stand out prominently. On Saturn, they modestly enhance atmospheric belt visibility. Red filters pass roughly 25% of light (#23A is lighter than #25), meaning views darken somewhat but remain comfortable.</p>

          <p><strong>Orange #21 (Orange filter):</strong> Similar benefits to red filters but lighter (passes more light, approximately 44%). Good starting filter for Jupiter showing enhanced belt contrast and improved GRS visibility. Works well on Mars for surface features. Many observers prefer #21 over #23A/#25 for its brighter image while still providing good contrast enhancement.</p>

          <p><strong>Light Blue #80A or #82A (Blue filters):</strong> Enhance high-altitude atmospheric features while suppressing lower-altitude detail. On Jupiter, blue filters increase contrast of bright zones and high-altitude features. On Mars, they highlight polar caps, ice clouds, dust storms, and atmospheric haze while suppressing surface albedo features—useful for studying Martian weather. On Saturn, they modestly enhance atmospheric bands. Blue filters pass roughly 70-80% of light, providing bright images.</p>

          <p><strong>Green #58 or Yellow-Green #11 (Green filters):</strong> Provide balanced enhancement showing multiple feature types moderately. #11 yellow-green works well for Mars, showing both surface markings and atmospheric phenomena. On Jupiter, green filters offer compromise between red and blue filter effects.</p>

          <p><strong>Violet #47 (UV filter):</strong> Specialized filter for Venus' atmospheric clouds, which absorb UV and violet wavelengths creating faint dark patterns in upper atmosphere. These patterns are invisible unfiltered but occasionally appear as subtle markings through #47 filters. Requires excellent optics, good seeing, and substantial aperture (8+ inches) to detect. Not useful for other planets.</p>

          <h3>Filter Selection Strategy</h3>
          <p>For beginners starting planetary observing, purchase a basic three-filter set: <strong>#21 Orange</strong> (Jupiter, Mars), <strong>#80A Light Blue</strong> (atmospheric features all planets), and <strong>#23A Light Red</strong> (Mars, Jupiter). These three filters costing $20-30 each cover 90% of planetary observing needs. As experience grows, add <strong>#11 Yellow-Green</strong> for Mars, <strong>#58 Green</strong> for additional contrast options, and <strong>#47 Violet</strong> if attempting Venus atmospheric observations.</p>

          <p>During observing sessions, keep multiple filters accessible and compare views. The "best" filter varies by planet, atmospheric conditions, feature type, and telescope optics. Many nights, one filter clearly shows features better; other nights, differences appear subtle. Experienced observers switch filters frequently, using the one revealing target features most clearly. Don't rely on filter recommendations exclusively—experiment and use your eyes to judge effectiveness.</p>

