          <h2>Magnification Requirements by Planet</h2>
          <p>Planetary observing demands higher magnifications than most deep sky work to resolve small planetary disks and show fine details. However, more magnification isn't always better—atmospheric seeing and optical quality limit practical maximum magnification.</p>

          <h3>General Principles</h3>
          <p>Useful magnification ranges depend on planetary apparent size and desired detail level. <strong>Minimum magnification</strong> to resolve a planet as a disk (not a point) equals approximately 25x per arcsecond of planetary diameter. For Jupiter (45 arcseconds at opposition): 25×45≈110x minimum to show disk and basic features. For Mars (20 arcseconds during favorable opposition): 25×20≈50x minimum to show disk (but needs more for details). <strong>Optimal magnification</strong> balances detail visibility with image brightness and seeing limitations—typically 1.5-3× the minimum magnification. <strong>Maximum practical magnification</strong> is limited by atmospheric seeing (rarely exceeds 250-300x even under excellent conditions) and telescope diffraction limit (typically 50x per inch aperture).</p>

          <h3>Planet-Specific Recommendations</h3>
          <p><strong>Jupiter:</strong> 100x-150x shows full disk with major belts and zones clearly visible—excellent "showcase" view for visitors. 150x-200x reveals GRS, belt structure, zone details, and festoons. 200x-300x during excellent seeing resolves finest atmospheric details, small white ovals, and complex festoon patterns. Most Jupiter observing occurs at 120-180x where detail and seeing stability optimize.</p>

          <p><strong>Saturn:</strong> 100x-150x provides beautiful full-system view with rings, Cassini Division, and globe all visible comfortably. 150x-200x shows ring subdivisions, subtle atmospheric bands, and ring shadow details. 200x-250x during excellent seeing resolves finest ring structure though Saturn benefits less from extreme magnification than Jupiter due to lower atmospheric contrast. Many observers find 120-150x produces the most aesthetically pleasing Saturn views balancing detail with system completeness.</p>

          <p><strong>Mars:</strong> Due to Mars' small size, it requires higher magnifications than the larger gas giants. 150x minimum to see basic polar caps and major albedo features. 200x-250x reveals good detail during favorable oppositions showing ice caps clearly, major dark markings like Syrtis Major, and bright desert regions. 250x-350x during excellent seeing and favorable opposition resolves finest surface details, subtle atmospheric phenomena, and hints of major geological features. During unfavorable oppositions when Mars appears 14-16 arcseconds, even 300x provides disappointing views—Earth-Mars distance overwhelms optical capability.</p>

          <p><strong>Venus:</strong> 80x-120x shows phase shape clearly—higher magnification dims the brilliant disk without revealing additional detail (no surface features visible through atmosphere). Occasionally push to 150x-180x when attempting UV atmospheric observation with #47 filter.</p>

          <p><strong>Mercury:</strong> 100x-150x shows phase adequately given small size (maximum 13 arcseconds). Higher magnification (180x-200x) may show phase more clearly but risks excessive image dimming and atmospheric turbulence effects near horizon.</p>

          <p><strong>Uranus and Neptune:</strong> 150x minimum to confidently resolve disk (versus star-like point). 200x-250x shows disk more clearly and reveals color. Higher magnifications provide marginal benefit given tiny sizes (Uranus 3.7", Neptune 2.3")—primarily they confirm non-stellar nature.</p>

          <h3>Calculating Required Eyepieces</h3>
          <p>Calculate eyepiece focal length by dividing telescope focal length by desired magnification: Focal Length ÷ Magnification = Eyepiece Focal Length. Example: 1000mm focal length telescope, target magnification 150x: 1000÷150≈6.7mm eyepiece. Round to available eyepiece sizes (6mm or 7mm).</p>

          <p>Recommended planetary eyepiece set: <strong>15mm eyepiece</strong> (low power for finding/overview), <strong>10mm eyepiece</strong> (medium power for general planetary), <strong>6-7mm eyepiece</strong> (medium-high power for details), <strong>4-5mm eyepiece</strong> (high power for excellent seeing nights). Alternatively, use a 2x or 3x Barlow lens with medium-focal-length eyepieces to reach higher magnifications economically—a 10mm eyepiece with 2x Barlow yields 2000mm telescope focal length: 2000÷10=200x.</p>
